\section{Introduction}

\begin{frame}
  \center{\fcolorbox{green}{white}{\bf Introduction}}
\begin{center} {\scriptsize
{\bf Neutron Stars: What we know and what we do not know.}}
The determination of the equation of state of cold, ultradense matter, such as that found in the interiors of neutron stars, has been one of the key science goals of high-energy astrophysics and nuclear physics. Low mass X-ray binaries that show thermonuclear X-ray bursts are ideal sources to put constraints on the equation of state of neutron star matter. Lack of independent distance measurements for most of these sources, however, prevents a systematic exploration of the mass and radius of these neutron stars, and hence the equation of state at such nuclear densities.
We perform time resolved spectral analyses of the X-ray bursts observed from the low-mass X-ray binaries, and combine the results of this analysis with a novel distance measurement technique, based on near-IR observations of red clump stars along the line of sight and high
energy resolution X-ray spectra of X-ray binaries. When combined, these two analyses enable independent measurements of the neutron star mass and radius.
\end{center}
\end{frame}







%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection*{Physics of NS}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Physics of NS}  
 % \begin{columns}[c]
  %  \begin{column}{0.6\textwidth}  
	{\scriptsize 
	  \begin{itemize}
	   \item More than 2000 NSs have been discovered in the Galaxy, from pulsating sources in radio to bright persistent sources in X-Rays.
	   \item Stellar objects with most extreme densities and strongest magnetic fields.
	   \item Strongest gravitational fields among all objects with a surface.
	   \item NS Studies:
	    \begin{itemize}
	     \item Dynamics of binary systems,
	     \item structure and energetics of radio pulses,
	     \item spectra and variability of their high energy radiation,
	     \item direct observations of the emission of NS surface.
	    \end{itemize}
	    \item NS Surfaces:
	      \begin{itemize}
	       \item often hidden from view,
	       \item overpowered by non-thermal magnetospheric emission in isolated sources or accretion luminosity from binaries.
	       \item however, evidences of surface emission from:
		\begin{itemize}
		 \item isolated cooling NS
		 \item accreting sournces during quiescence,
		 \item thermonuclear bursters,
		 \item isolated NS powered by magnetic field.
		\end{itemize}
	      \end{itemize}
	  \end{itemize}
	}       
